text.doc:
The <strong><code>Text</code></strong> interface represents a text <a href="$MDN_URL$/Web/API/Node" ><code>node</code></a> in a DOM tree.
<p>To understand what a text node is, consider the following document:
<div class="code-example"><p class="example-header"><span class="language-name"><pre class="brush: html notranslate"><code>&lt;html lang="en" class="e"&gt;
  &lt;head&gt;
    &lt;title&gt;Aliens?&lt;/title&gt;
  &lt;/head&gt;
  &lt;body&gt;
    Why yes.
  &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
</code></pre></span></div>
<p>In that document, there are five text nodes, with the following contents:
<ul>
<li><code>"\n "</code> (after the <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> start tag, a newline followed by four spaces)</li>
<li><code>"Aliens?"</code> (the contents of the <code>title</code> element)</li>
<li><code>"\n "</code> (after the <code>&lt;/head&gt;</code> end tag, a newline followed by two spaces)</li>
<li><code>"\n "</code> (after the <code>&lt;body&gt;</code> start tag, a newline followed by two spaces)</li>
<li><code>"\n Why yes.\n \n\n"</code> (the contents of the <code>body</code> element)</li>
</ul>
<p>Each of those text nodes is an object that has the properties and methods documented in this article.
